File: platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/analyze-site/detect-auth.ts, lines 118-122.

Current implementation:
```typescript
const looksLikeJwt = (value: string): boolean => {
  const parts = value.split('.');
  if (parts.length !== 3) return false;
  return parts.every(p => p.length > 0 && BASE64URL_SEGMENT.test(p));
};
```

This matches any 3-segment dotted string where each segment is base64url. Version strings like '1.2.3' pass because digits are valid base64url.

Fix: Add a minimum total length check. Real JWT headers are base64-encoded JSON objects (minimum ~36 chars for the header segment). A simple fix: require each segment to be at least 10 characters, or require a minimum total string length of ~40 characters. The most robust fix: try to base64url-decode the first segment and check if it parses as JSON with an 'alg' key.

Recommended approach: Add `parts.every(p => p.length >= 10)` as an additional check. This filters out all version strings while keeping real JWTs (which have segments of 30+ characters).

